An '''expeditor''' is someone who facilitates a process. It is a position or role found within [[project management]], [[construction]], [[purchasing]] and [[production control]]. One example of this is a person in a restaurant who coordinates actions between cooks and wait staff in a restaurant, managing the flow of orders and giving real-time commands to other employees.
In a shipping logistics [[supply chain]], an expeditor's role is primarily to look at the requirement levels in the business and fulfill the demands by either rescheduling in or rescheduling out the delivery date on the [[purchase order]]. The expeditor is also responsible for making sure there is no line stopping situation for a business. The key metrics which an expeditor influences may be - Ontime Delivery, Cash Flow Cycle and Inventory Management. An expeditor needs to be assertive and needs to know the business at high contextual levels<ref>{{citation|title=The high-tech career book|page=104|author=Betsy A. Collard|year=1986}}</ref>
Also the name used for Beech 18 aircraft by British and Commonwealth air forces (1940s-50s).
