{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Lenny Curry |image =LennyCurryJAX.jpg |office = [[Mayor of Jacksonville]] |term_start = July 1, 2015 |term_end = |predecessor = [[Alvin Brown]] |successor = |office2 = Chair of the [[Florida Republican Party]] |term_start2 = 2011 |term_end2 = 2014 |predecessor2 = [[David Bitner]] |successor2 = [[Leslie Dougher]] |governor2 = [[Rick Scott]] |birth_name = Leonard Boyd Curry |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|7|19}} |birth_place = [[Key West, Florida]], U.S. |death_date = |death_place = |party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] |spouse = Molly Curry |children = |alma_mater = [[University of Florida]] |religion = [[Methodist]] |website = {{url|http://www.coj.net/mayor.aspx|Office of the Mayor}} }} '''Leonard Boyd Curry''' (born July 19, 1970) is an American politician and businessman who is currently [[List of mayors of Jacksonville, Florida|Mayor]] of [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. He assumed office on July 1, 2015, after defeating incumbent [[Alvin Brown]] in the city's [[Jacksonville mayoral election, 2015|2015 mayoral election]]. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Curry formerly served as chairman of the [[Republican Party of Florida]] and co-founded the professional services firm ICX Group.
==Life and career== Curry was born in [[Key West, Florida|Key West]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cassidy|first1=Austin|title=Meet Lenny Curry: The Republican Party’s Quarterback for 2010|url=http://www.jaxobserver.com/2010/08/30/the-gops-quarterback-meet-lenny-curry/|website=Jacksonville Observer|accessdate=March 26, 2016|date=August 30, 2010}}</ref> He later grew up in [[Middleburg, Florida]] and graduated from [[Middleburg High School]]. Curry began his higher education at [[St. Johns River State College|St. Johns River Community College]], then transferred to the [[University of Florida]] and graduated ''summa cum laude'' with a degree in accounting.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Monroe|first1=Nate|title=Curry transformed from minor player in GOP politics to formidable Brown challenger|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/2015-03-05/story/curry-transformed-minor-player-gop-politics-formidable-brown-challenger|website=Florida Times-Union|accessdate=March 26, 2016|date=March 5, 2015}}</ref> He married his wife, Molly, in 2005. They have three children: Boyd, Brook, and Bridgett.<ref name="young">{{cite news|url=https://www.jaxdailyrecord.com/showstory.php?Story_id=543092|title=The story behind Lenny Curry's decision to run for Jacksonville mayor|author=Marilyn Young|date=June 3, 2014|publisher=Financial News & Daily Record|accessdate=May 20, 2015}}</ref>
From 1994 to 2002, he practiced as a certified public accountant at [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]. In 2002, he co‐founded a Jacksonville-based professional services firm, ICX Group Inc., providing finance and accounting consulting, executive recruiting, and staffing services.
On June&nbsp;3, 2014, Curry filed to run in the [[Jacksonville mayoral election, 2015|Jacksonville mayoral election in 2015]]. He decided to enter the race because beginning in late 2012 and early 2013, he began hearing about "leadership troubles" under incumbent Democratic mayor [[Alvin Brown]].<ref name="young"/> [[File: Mike Pence and Rick Scott.jpg|thumb|left|[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] meeting with [[Governor of Florida|Florida Governor]] [[Rick Scott]] and [[Mayor of Jacksonville|Jacksonville Mayor]] Lenny Curry.]]
